,Recommended,214170,19975404,"Posted: 26 December, 2015",all,squareular,"I'm still very, very early on in the game, but as I'm now on my fourth character start, there are some things I'd like to tell myself from two days ago:Save the game, you moron. Save it often, else when you die you have to redo all the things.The game will not help you on how to play it. Go read some guides and forums to figure out how the game works. Even if that's not ""doing it right,"" it is how YOU will have more fun. You like solving puzzles and quests; not puzzling out how your stats work.Yes, I know you like playing blaster mages, but you'll soon learn that you like playing blaster mages when you have another player acting as a tank to keep the enemies from all rushing you. You will be terrified of everything and die a lot.While Survivor and Wizard look like cool classes, they are harder to play. You have no strategy yet. Go play a warrior.While the female warrior is off putting in a chainmail bikini, you will soon pick up more armor and therefore be clothed.In reference to the above point, it is in your best interest to steal everything you can get ahold of when no one is looking. There are no negative consequences to stealing if you don't get caught.It is okay to go outside of the village without having finished everything there. In fact do so, kill some orcs, level up, and then go back to the catacombs.Your fears about the graphics looking bad are baseless, since you've barely played any computer games in the past decade and this is still what you expect computer games to look like.All in all I'm greatly enjoying myself. I love exploring everywhere I possibly can and this game greatly encourages that."
76561197978131107,Recommended,214170,31475539,Posted: 30 April,all,Superbeef,"As a huge fan of ""Original Sin"", I wanted to experience this series' roots. If you have tolerance for old school gaming, and enjoy the newer Divinity games, and canoverlook some mechanics that haven't aged wellyou can find some fun here. There the imp ZixZax, and the leveling system you love, and a zombie named Jake, and a healing stone that you can give to a mortally wounded solder (or hoard for yourself), and you can throw items all over the place and look for hidden keys and levers, and there's all those fun skills that feel like true stepping stones when you first obtain them.The first area is a multilevel catacombs with puzzles and a few interesting and goofy characters and I'm thinking I can overlook the diablo-esqe combat system involving (mostly) clicking on a unit until they die. But then the baloney starts. There's these champions who will kill you in a couple hits, and unless you want to try to run past them, you are going to have to tough it out.  I finally got past the first few by kiting around them for 5 minutes and chipping away at their health with a little bow and arrow. Then, the next level down, there's like 10 more champions in a single area. Huh?I finally ""solved"" it by powergaming and abusing skill systems. Ah-ha! The scorpion traps that the thief class has are absolutely gamebreaking. They can clear out a map solo with a little help. Cool! Powergaming in Divinity games is always my favorite part, and I was amused to see that in the 1st game, it was not merely optional as it wasrequired.So I solve that part, and I learn a bunch more skills, I get my teleport pyramids set up so I can warp back to a bedroom and heal up in a snap. I start doing sidequests. And there's still a lot of grinding, more than I'm comfortable with, but it's bearable and I was looking forward to each new level-up to see what I could do.I make it about halfway into the game - I think - because there's still parts of the map that are inexplicably tough, but then my teleporter pyramids are taken away for story reasons, and I have to fight my way out of a crypt. The story is interesting leading up to this, but apparently I triggered this quest way too early because I'm about 15 levels too far behind and even my tricks don't save me now. It takes me six hours of kiting enemies to make it out alive and get back on the road. But my teleporter pyramids aren't returned yet. I check a guide and I've got to get about 10 hours down the main questline before I get them back.That means grinding my character a LOT more, and now I have to do it without the benefit of fast travel back to town for a quick heal. No way. Not going to happen.  This is where I signed off.I don't regret my time spent with ""Divine Divinity"" but I won't be finishing it, and I'd only suggest playing it if you want to see where it all began. Or, even better, do it with a walkthrough guidiing your course, and don't make the same unrecoverable mistakes I made."
