,Recommended,214170,9335289,"Posted: 3 March, 2014",all,Xendarii,"You can find a comprehensive review of the game below the pros and cons, as well as a summarizing conclusion right at the end.Pros+ Overall nice main plot+ Up to 60-70 hours play time+ Great and varying quests+ A vast number of weapons and items+ Mostly coherent atmosphere+ Good soundtrackCons- Outdated graphics- A bunch of bugs and technical issues- Weak last story chapter- Some world design inconsistenciesGameplayDivine Divinity has intuitive controls, a clear user interface (although this does not apply for the inventory) and offers some comfort features like hotkeys, a minimap and a great quest log. The battles are simple, but can get a little bit confusing when you're surrounded by many enemies or have to fight behind obstacles. Also, there's not much tactic needed (and possible) - you either end up clicking opponent after opponent to smash them to bits or do the same thing from the distance with arrows or spells. The game's pretty challenging especially at the beginning though, when you're low on health and don't deal much damage, but gets a lot easier once you've got good armor and a powerful weapon (or spells, if you're playing as a mage). Divine Divinity perfectly evokes your drive for more and better items and constantly satisfies it, since enemies often drop useful things and there are chests full of great loot around every corner.The huge downside of this game is that it's got a pretty weak technology. I experienced regular crashes or hang-ups - sometimes without an accountable reason, sometimes when I tried to open a book or pick up an item. That's annoying, but can be compensated by saving often and on different savegames. What's worse is that some core mechanics are either buggy or completely inoperative. There are some skills that don't have an effect on battles even if they're expected to, others are extremely overpowered and you can break several quests by entering certain areas earlier than intended by the developers or using the (unapparantly) wrong speech options. This worsens the overall impression and tempers the gaming experience constantly.Story & QuestsThe storyline is key to every good role-playing game, and while you certainly cannot expect Divine Divinity to have the greatest plot ever seen in the gaming industry, its golden thread is enjoyable and sometimes even a bit exciting. The presentation isn't always perfectly well-made, however - some dialogs seem clumsy, some core parts of the story are treated too hasty and the last (and fortunately short) part of the game is pretty boring and doesn't match up to the rest of the game.A huge strong point of Divine Divinity are its quests. They are almost always specific in one way or the other - be it because of an unexpected turn, very bizarre characters or a good portion of humour. The game keeps the typical ""Bring me 25 red flowers"" or ""Kill 20 orcs"" quests within a limit, but provides lots of side quests to stop you from following the main quest nevertheless.While the game's general atmosphere is quite nice and consistent, particularly in certain areas like Aleroth, the village in which you get started, or a huge forest in the south of the game's main region, there are a few things that sometimes take you out of the illusion to be a part of an authentic and comprehensible world. The bettermost example for this issue are the elves, one of Rivellon's most important races, who can get very old, and therefore could be expected to reach wisdom and calmness in the process, but instead mostly act like pubescent humans. Things like these may be dependent on personal preferences, but are one reason why Divine Divinity can not quite match up to the real RPG greats.Graphics & SoundIf the graphics are the or at least one of the most important parts of a game for you, you definitely should beware of even thinking about playing Divine Divinity. I mostly liked its style and wasn't bothered about that it doesn't even look exceptionally good for a twelve years old game, but that's something every player has to decide for himself by looking at screenshots or watching videos.The situation is different with the sound, which is some kind of a two-edged sword. On the one hand, the effects aren't anything to speak of and I experienced a very disturbing and loud noise interference on some rare occasions. The music, however, is always enjoyable and the score has got some outstanding pieces that are capable of adding a lot more atmosphere to the situations they accompany.ConclusionDivine Divinity might not be one of the greatest games in history, but it offers many hours of an unfeigend and nostalgic adventure that will make you want to come back to the lands of Rivellon whenever possible and stay as long as you can. The game offers a good mix of story elements and battles to make sure that both Hack and Slay as well as RPG fans will get their money worth and will entertain you with around 60 hours of fun (given you take your time to discover every corner of the world and solve all the side quests). There are some flaws, and some of them aren't negligible, but if you aren't addicted to amazing graphics and don't get frustrated by games with some rough edges, you certainly should not miss out on an exciting journes to this fantastic world."
