,Recommended,214170,8991809,"Posted: 5 February, 2014",all,mr3,"Can't believe I never took the time to play this sooner.  As far as RPGs go it's in the big leagues.  It starts off slow, and the 1st major challenge is a little much, but the freaking thing sucks you in like crack.  It's smooth cracksmoke sailing from there on out as far as I can tell.  The closest thing I can think of to describe it is Diablo 1 with a much much much bigger world and combat a hair behind it (not much, just minor stuff).  Half of the problem is missing convenience controls like a stand-still-while♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥button, and not-so-much-ease in other combat controls like switching weapons (lots of things you can hotkey, some things seem like you can't though).  The other half is the engine itself: it doesn't schedule work well, so when it gets enough on the screen at once it starts ignoring control input, which engine design should never allow.  It happens *rarely* though (so far only with lots of projectiles in flight), and it may have been fine at release (coulda just been DX6- approaches to drawing that weren't properly dealt with in the update), so it's not a big deal for me.  The issue shows itself in lack of Steam overlay support too, by the way.  Aggravating, but the game is way way worth it.  The story is as big and seemingly non-linear as the world, and the number of quests and quest complexity matches it.  Alongside that is significant ability customization, and different layouts do seem to matter in most ways you'd expect.  It's got the cheeziest humor, so bad it's good, and speaking of that the voice acting is freaking horrrrrific.  The next one in the series better be as bad, I'm looking forward to the (un)intended humor.  Best of all, it's one of those games where you can tell how much the dev team loved it--there's attention to detail all around, and it wasn't rushed out so fast it didn't get needed polish.  All in all, 94/100 for me."
